{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_broadwick_ver01/data/sn93065779/00279558236/1945112601/0507.xml":{"full_text":"UNCOLN COUNTY\u2019S FAVORITE FAMILY NEWSPAPER\nThis Week in\nWASHINGTON\nWashington, D. C. (NWNS)\nAlthough many people may be dis\nappointed in the accomplishments of\nthe labor-management conference to\ndate, it is th e general consensus of\nopinion here that it cannot end in\ncomplete failure. For, even though\nfew agreements may be reached\nwhich will help solve labor-manage\nment problems, the conference al\nready has done a great deal toward\ndefining the differences which exist\nbetween labor and management. That\naccomplishment in itself, will make\nit easier for Congress, for. the ad\nministration, and for business and\nlabor to seek practical solutions.\nOne congressman commented:\n\u201cMembers of Congress, most of\nwhom are closely following the pro\ncedure of the conference, are going\nto have a clearer picture than they\never did before of what this epi\ndemic of strikes is all about. It is\ngoing to help us a lot in determin\ning whether new labor legislation is\nnecessary, and if so, what kinds of\nlegislation will do ttye most good.\nThis whole problem is now getting\np good airing\u2014and that is what has\nbeen needed.\u201d\nLittle action on labor legislation\nis expected until the conference is\nover\u2014until both labor and manage\nment have put all of their cards on\nthe table. Then legislation will un\ndoubtedly be sought aimed at reduc\ning the \u201carea of differences.\u201d\n\nMeanwhile, the figbt between tiie\nautomobile workers and the automo\nbile manufacturers has reached the\npoint where the public is demanding\nan early settlement. Reports that\nthe 500,000 automobiles expected to\nbe produced in 1945 has now dwin\ndled to less than a quarter of that\nfigure has aroused a car-hungry\npublic, and letters pouring in to Con\ngress reveal that the public is not\nonly concerned over getting new au\ntomobiles, but is increasingly fearful\nthat the delay may disrupt our na-\nPre-Holiday Values for\nEarly Gift Shoppers\n<i\nBaby Carriage*, all steel $14.95 Child\u2019s Rockers $2.00\nAll-Metal Strollers $12.50 Baby Swing with spring $2.75\nCarpet for hall and staircase, Kitchen Stool, wood $3.75\nwo y ar Kitchen Stool, all aluminum $5.45\nPictures, all sizes.\n2- Living Room Suites, Coffee Tables $5.25 up\nin velours and tapestry $109.50 Studio Couches $69.50\n3- Living Rc|om Suites, Mirrows, plate, good selection $8.75 up\nin velours auid tapestry $139.50 3-piece Bedroom Suites, poster\n100% All Wool Blankets $15.95 bed $69.50\nTable Lamps $9.95 up Pillows, all feather; pair $2.95 up\nEnd Tables $1.95 up Magazine Racks $2.95\nWhat Nots $9.95 High Chairs $6.50 up\nBook Cases $11.9$ Rebuilt Singer Sewing Machines\nChild\u2019s Table and Chair Sets $7.95 Dining Room Suites $149.50\nSee Our 1946 Model Leonard Refrigerator and Bendix Home\nLaundry Now On Display\u2014Place Your Orders Now\nGoodin-Burris Furn. Co.\nPhone 259-J. LINCOLNTON,-N. C.\ntion\u2019s reconversion program.\nThere also has been considerable\nobjection to the fact that automo\nbiles which are on display do not\nhave any price tags on them, as is\nalso the case with a good number of\nother items on the consumers\u2019 \u201chigh\npriority\u201d list. The public, apparent\nly, wants to start buying these items\nnow\u2014to get in line with cash pay\nments\u2014but they don\u2019t want to buy\n\u201ca pig in a poke\u201d so far as price\nis concerned. Manufacturers are be\ncoming equally insistent that the\ngovernment end its delay in agreeing\nto ceiling prices.\n\nIn the most interesting press con\nference which Clinton Anderson has\nheld since he became secretary of\nagriculture, he revealed that meat\nrationing will probably be all over\nby the end of the year, that our ci\nvilian food supply will hereafter be\nmuch better than \u201ceven in prewar\nyears.\u201d\nMr. Anderson also released figures\non our program for helping hungry\nEurobe during the rest of the year.\nHe said that our exports of food to\nthe United Kingdom, liberated coun\ntries in Europe and French North\nAfrica would be increased by about\n50 per cent during the last quarter\nof the year.\nPointing out the enormity of our\nfood supply, the secretary indicated\nthat our shipments to other countries\ncould be still greater, without any\nshortages at home. The only thing\nwhich is preventing greater ship\nments, he said, is the regulations re\ngarding such shipments and the fin\nancial difficulties involved. Total food\nshipments in the last quarter will be\nabout 4,500,000 tons.\nMr. Anderson, who favors getting\nrid of subsidies as soon as the time\nis ripe, indicated that some subsidies\nmay be terminated soon even though\nit may result in increased prices.\nThe wild blueberry has been bred\ninto an excellent fruit grown in cul\ntivated fields of Eastern Carolina on\nacid soils that would have otherwise\nproduced only brush and scrubby for\nest growth.\nTo the People\nof this Community\nLeave It to the nation\u2019s school\nchildren to be on top of the ball\nwhen It comes to sizing up the war\nfinancing situation. From Pearl\nHarbor to V-J\nfj Day they dedi\n(\\wjfA cattd each pur\n'djMMjK chase and sale\nof war bands to\nm'vv. \"ft fighting equlp-\nVJlifMlii ment. Then the\nSchools at War\ncame Schools\nFor Peace. The\ntheme shifted from \u201cBack the At\ntack\" to \u201cSpeed His Recovery.\" The\nnew goal was set at 35,000 hospital\nunits, Including a bed, wheel chair,\nX-Ray machine and surgical Instru\nments.\nGrownups could well listen to one\nof the millions of youngsters who\nare taking part In the Victory Loan.\nEven without a word from the young\nvolunteer, you have one of the main\nreasons for buying extra Victory\nBonds\u2014the future of the \u201csalesman\"\nwho may be your own son or daugh\nter. Your war bonds have Just\nhelped to defeat the Nazis and Japs\nwho would have educated your chil\ndren for death. Your extra Victory\nBonds will assure a brighter life for\ntomorrow\u2019s citizens.\nTHE EDITOR\nWilliam F. Poston\nPromoted to Corporal\nBase M, San Fernando, La Union,\nLuzon, P\u201e I. William F. Poston,\nhusband of Mrs. Annie Lorene Pos\nton, East Pine Street, Lincolnton,\nNorth Carolina, a clerk in the 4459th\nQuartermaster Service Company, has\nrecently been promoted to Corporal\nat this large Central Luzon Base\n\u201cM.\u201d\nCorporal Poston entered the serv\nice in September 1942, and was sent\noverseas to Europe in February of\nthis year where he took part in the\ndrive across Europe, before being re\ndeployed to the Western Pacific.\nA graduate of Oaklawn High, he\nwears one battle star on his Euro\npean-African-Middle Eastern Thea\ntre ribbon.\nTHE LINCOLN TIMES, LINCOLNTON, N. C, MONDAY, NOV. 26, 1945\nFarmers to Elect AAA\nCommitteemen Nov. 30\nRaleigh, N. C., Nov. 24. Over\n350,000 Tar Heel farmers will have\nthe opportunity on Nov. 30 to go to\nthe polls and elect more than 9,000\nactive farmers who will sit down\nwith them and help plan a conserva\ntion program based on actual needs\nof their farms to speed reconversion\nof the State\u2019s farmland from the\nstrain of wartime production, R.\nFlake Shaw, Secretary, North Caro\nlina Farm Bureau Federation, point\ned out this week.\nj \u201cA large \u2018vote of confidence\u2019 will\nenable elected AAA Committeemen\nto do their job with the knowledge\nthat their neighbors ar e supporting\nthem,\u201d Shaw said.\n\u201cOne of the main programs that\nthe newly elected AAA committee\nmen will administer during the com\ning year is the 1946 Agriculture Con\nservation Program,\u201d he declared.\n\u201cThe conservation program, this year,\nhas been decentralized, with counties\nand communities allocated funds for\ndeveloping their own soil and water\nconservation practices,\u201d he continued.\n\u201cTo speed reconversion of the\nState\u2019s farmland from the strain of\nwartime production, the most capable\nfarm leaders in the counties and\ncommunities are needed,\u201d he explain\ned.\n\u201cThe AAA always has taken the\nposition that those operations which\nare intimately tied up with the farm\ner\u2019s economic welfare can best be ad\nministered by the farmer himself.\nMany grave problems lie ahead for\nagriculture and I hope that every\neligible farmer in the State will at\ntend his local election meeting and\nvoice his opinion for the men of his\nchoice to represent him considering\nthe problems and demands of the\ncoming year,\u201d Shaw concluded.\nEvery farmer in the State will re\nceive a notice as to the time and\nplace of the election meetings in his\ncommunity.\n14,000 Pounds Os\nTurkeys Destroyed\nA* Unfit For Use\nCharlotte, Nov. 22.\u2014Destruction of\n14,000 pounds of contaminated dress\ned turkeys brought t 0 the local mar\nket yesterday was announced by city\nhealth officials.\nSeizure of the fowls, they said,\nwas made by City Inspector William\nC. Mclntire and Shelby Grey, pure\nfood and drug inspector.\nThe fowls were brought to Char- j\nlotte by truck and seized on arrival.\nThey were disposed of in the city\u2019s\nincinerator.\n\"'666\nCOLD PREPARATIONS\nLiquid, Tablets, Salve, Nose Drops.\nCaution use only as directed.\nJake Rhodes Jack Rhodes\nWe want to thank the good people of this section\nfor the splendid reception given us upon our entry into\nLincolnton\u2019s business circles.\nYour response to our invitation to visit our station\nhas been most generous, and greatly appreciated. We\nhope you will continue to think of \u201cJake and Jack\u201d\nand remember we sell the well-known TEXACO pro\nducts and can give your car COMPLETE service.\nTexaco Service Station\nJake and Jack Rhodes, Props.\nPhone 9114 East Main Street Lincolnton, N. C.\nReceives Discharge\nmm m\nSeymour Johnson Field, N. C., Nov. j\n26 \u2014S/Sgt. James D. Knuckles, son of\nMr. and Mrs. L. A. Knuckles, 105 N.\nHigh street, Lincolnton, North Caro\nlina, Thursday was honorably dis\ncharged from the Army Air Forces\nat this First Air Force Separation\nBase.\nS/Sgt. Knuckles, a student at Lin\ncolnton High school in civilian life,\nentered the service on June 8, 1943,\nand served as an aerial gunner in\nItaly.\nHe holds the European theatre rib\nbon with two battle stars, the Amer\nican theatre ribbon, Good Conduct\nmedal, World War II Victory medal\nand is credited with 19 missions.\nFive Registrants To\nLeave For Ft. Bragg\nInduction notices have been mailed\nto the following colored registrants\nwho have been ordered to report to\nthe local board office, Monday, De\ncember 3, at 10:45 a. m. for trip to\nFt. Bragg for induction:\nJohn Shuford\nJosh Roberts\nHaywood Lewis\nCharlie James Clement\nFrederick Watts\nThe cotton South is on the thres\nhold of an industrial-agricultural\nrevolution that will shake its econ\nomy right down to the cotton roots,\nsays Secretary of Agriculture Clin\nton P. Anderson.\nRead the Want Ads i n The Times.\nFOR SALE\nCYPRESS\nPANELING\nSETH LUMBER CO.\nINCORPORATED m\nPhone 39 a\nMWW\u2014\u00ab\u25a0. i wsni\u00bb-\nScott Urges Farmers\nTo Vote in Election of\nAAA Committeemen\nI Raleigh, N. C., Nov. 24. \u2014Every\nfarmer has a vital interest in future\ndecisions of farm problems, whether\nlocal, State, or National, W. Kerr\nScott, Commissioner of Agriculture\nsaid here today in an effort to en\ncourage Tar Heel farmers to go to\ntheir community center and vote fn\nI the annual election of AAA commit-\nI teemen on November 30.\nUrging a full representative vote I\nin each of the 1,733 AAA communi\nties throughout the State, Scott de-1\ni plorey \u201cstay-at-home\u201d tendencies\namong some farmers, and appealed\nfor a full turn-out for this year\u2019s j\nelections.\nAbout 350,000 North Carolina'\nfarmers are eligible to vote in the'\nj coming elections.\nA total of 8,965 community com-1\n1 mitteemen and 100 delegates to coun-!\nty conventions are to be elected. Two 1\nalternate committeemen will also be'\nchosen for each community. The\ndelegates will elect three member\ncounty committeemen to administer 1\nAAA activities in each county.\n\u201cMany grave problems lie ahead\nfor agriculture,\u201d Scott asserted, \u201cand\nit is most important that these men\nhave the support of every eligible\nfarmer in their community.\u201d I\nLincolnton Business\nDirectory\nDAVE LERNER\nLincolnton, N. C.\nAgents for Complete Line\nWOLVERINE SHOES\nETCHISON HATS\nCARTER CO.\nLocated in New La wing Building\nPHONE 266\nALL FORMS OF\nINSURANCE\nPersonal Accident Tickets\nBy Day Or Year\nDR. I. R. SELF\nDR. I. R. SELF, JR.\nDENTISTS\nOffices: Over' La wing A Costner\u2019s\nDrug Store\nOffice Phone 85. Sea. Phone 118\nPAGE THREE\nA man who enlists or re-enlists in\nthe Regular Army before July first\nof 1946 may continue his family al\nlowances so rthe duration of his en\nlistment.\nWVWWSWVWWWWMWW\nexpert watch\nrepairing\nStroupe\u2019s Jewelers A Gift*\nhut Main Street\nAAWWWWVVMiwwwVWUWW\nBlack's Prescription\nFor Coughs and Colds\nInEcSwV\nDon\u2019t let that cough and cold\ncheat you out of a night\u2019s sleep.\nA quick relief called BLACK\u2019S\nPRESCRIPTION is now on sale\nat drug stores. Accept only the\ngenuine, packed i n the yellow car\nton.\nPrice 35 Cents\nWANTED\nYOU TO BRING, SEND\nOR PHONE ALL THE\nNEWS IN YOUK\nNEIGHBORHOOD TO\nThe Lincoln\nTimes\nLincolnton Insurance\nand Realty Co.\nReal Estate lnsurance\nV. M. Ramsaur\nPhone 201\n\u201cFurniture For Any Room\nIn Any Home.\u201d\nF.P. BARKLEY\nFurniture Store\nNorth Court Square.","height":"20655","width":"15055"}}
